title: Owly Murs: Tourist films dancing owl
text:
Owly Murs: Tourist films dancing owl Last updated 11:55, September 18 2015 REUTERS 
Holiday-goer films owl 'dancing' at UK wildlife park 
A young owl at a sanctuary in Cornwall, England, has captivated audiences with its dancing. 
Robert Cole caught the owl bobbing its head from side-to-side during a recent visit to the Screech Owl Sanctuary. 
The slick moves, caught on camera, even prompted Cole to rename the owlet "Owly Murs" in reference to British singer Olly Murs. ScreenGrab 
Baby owlet does the boogie at a sanctuary in England. 
Although it looks like the young bird is dancing, owls are known to bob their heads in that manner as a way of improving their depth perception, which helps visual development and the ability to perceive the distance of an object.
